String is a non-primitive Data Type in java 
String is a class in java
String are immutuable in java 

How to take input from user use Scanner class
1. one word : sc.next()
2. complete sentence including space : sc.nextLine();

=========================Important Methods of string=====================
1. length() : it return the number of chars string contains
example : s1.length();

2. concatenation : combine two strings 
s1+s2

3.charAt(index): return  the char present at given index
ex s1.charAt(i)

4. compareTo(String) : compare to string and return int value
example s1.compareTo(s2)
i) postive : if s1>s2
ii) equal : if s1==s2
iii) negative : if s1<s2
always use compareTo method to compare to string 
equal also works but use comapreTo

5. subString(startindex , endindex)
endindex is exlusive 
ex s1.subString(4,6)
return string of char present at 4,5th index


Strings are immutable 
cannot be modify , deleted once its created 
every time it will create new object in memory if we modify string and which take time


==================================StringBuilder==============================
With the help of StringBuilder string we can modify string  without creation of new objec

Declaration of StringBuilder

StringBuilder s=new StringBuilder("seema");

// we can not directly take input from user into StringBuilder object itself from System.in
as it return primitive types or String Object 


=============================Some Extra methods of StringBuilder=======================
1. setCharAt(idx , value ): set char at idx 
example s1.setCharAt(3,'s');

2. insert(idx,string): 
insert string a idx 
example :
s1.insert(1,"sangwan")

3. delete(start,end)
end is exlusive
delete from start to end-1
example s1.delete(3,6); // 345

4. append(string)
append a string in the end
s1.append("sangwan")

5. length()--> return length;
6. charAt(i) --> return char at given index;

